The paper deals with cross-modal hashing, which involves mapping heterogeneous multimedia data into a common Hamming space for fast and flexible retrieval across different modalities. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including computer vision (cs.CV), multimedia (cs.MM), information retrieval (cs.IR), machine learning (cs.LG), and computational linguistics (cs.CL). However, since the paper focuses on unsupervised cross-modal hashing using generative adversarial networks, it is most likely to belong to cs.CV, which deals with image and video processing, as well as deep learning and neural networks. The other sub-categories are also relevant, but to a lesser extent, since they may not specifically address the problem of cross-modal hashing or unsupervised learning.
